-- ─── 5. Amazon Retail Cold Start ───────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{
  "summary": "Design a hybrid cold-start recommendation system for brand-new retail items: rules and content-based retrieval for precision, generative retrieval for recall expansion, compatibility-aware ranking, and staged launch gating.",
  "outline": [
    "Phase 1 — Requirements: define surfaces, primary metric = attach rate or add-to-cart lift, cold-start means zero interaction history, and guardrails around irrelevance and compatibility",
    "Phase 2 — Candidate Generation: hybrid pool from taxonomy rules, dense content-based retrieval, and LLM-generated shopping-intent queries with metadata validation",
    "Phase 3 — Ranking: two-stage retrieval plus reranking using anchor-item metadata, candidate quality signals, pairwise compatibility features, and uncertainty penalties on generated intents",
    "Phase 4 — Evaluation: replay historical launches as synthetic cold-start test set, add human or LLM-judge review for semantic complementarity, then run conservative online experiments",
    "Phase 5 — Production: progressive handoff from cold-start logic to collaborative signals, monitoring for hallucinated intents and sparse-metadata failures, rollback on irrelevance spikes"
  ],
  "full_response": "I would start by clarifying where these recommendations show up and what business outcome we care about. If this is the product detail page or add-to-cart flow, the primary metric should be attach rate or add-to-cart lift, not click-through alone. We also need guardrails: irrelevance rate, compatibility failures, diversity across complementary categories, and no degradation to the main item''s conversion. The defining constraint is that the anchor item is brand new, so there is no co-view or co-purchase history to lean on.\n\nFor candidate generation, I would use a hybrid strategy because no single method is reliable enough in true cold start. First, a rules and taxonomy layer gives high-precision complements where domain knowledge is strong, like laptop to sleeve or camera to SD card. Second, content-based retrieval uses the new item''s title, category, brand, price band, attributes, and image embedding to retrieve candidates from a dense index. Third, I would add a generative retrieval path where an LLM turns the item metadata into shopping-intent queries such as ''ergonomic office accessories for standing desk'' and then uses the standard search stack to retrieve complements. That path improves recall and creativity, but only after metadata validation so bad catalog attributes do not produce nonsense intents.\n\nRanking is where we control quality. I would keep a two-stage setup: a lightweight retrieval layer for recall, then a reranker using pairwise compatibility features. The anchor item contributes title, category, brand, price range, attributes, and image features. Candidate items contribute historical quality metrics such as conversion, return rate, inventory health, shipping speed, and ratings. The key features are pairwise: category complementarity, price compatibility, use-case coherence, and brand or accessory compatibility. Generated-intent candidates should carry an uncertainty feature so the model can down-rank them unless other evidence agrees.\n\nFor offline evaluation, I would replay historical item launches as synthetic cold-start examples. For each item, hide its early interaction history, generate recommendations using only metadata, and score against later observed attach behavior. Metrics would include precision@k, NDCG, attach-rate prediction, diversity, and compatibility error rate. Because offline behavior is noisy, I would add human review or LLM-as-judge for semantic complementarity and obvious irrelevance. Online, I would start with conservative traffic slices or high-confidence categories first and require attach-rate lift without hurting main-item conversion.\n\nIn production, the most important design choice is the handoff from cold-start to normal recommendation logic. As the item gathers clicks, carts, and purchases, I would progressively increase the weight of collaborative signals and decrease the weight of generated intents. A bandit policy can gather signal without flooding uncertain candidates. Monitoring should track hallucinated intents, sparse-metadata failures, compatibility complaints, seller bias, and return-rate spikes. If generated intents start producing irrelevant or misleading recommendations, I would immediately roll back to the rules-plus-content baseline while investigating the metadata or prompt failure."
}'::jsonb
WHERE category = 'design' AND subcategory = 'Amazon Retail Cold Start';


-- ─── 6. LLM Judge Evaluation Platform ──────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{
  "summary": "Design a production evaluation platform that uses LLM-as-judge with surface-specific rubrics, human calibration, offline-online validation, and drift monitoring to gate launches of generative systems.",
  "outline": [
    "Phase 1 — Requirements: define outputs being judged, quality taxonomy, and how judge scores influence launch decisions rather than replacing them",
    "Phase 2 — Judge Architecture: surface-specific rubrics, structured JSON scores, evidence capture, and selective use of expensive multi-judge evaluation for high-risk cases",
    "Phase 3 — Calibration: human gold sets, agreement metrics, threshold calibration into ship / investigate / block decisions, and disagreement workflows",
    "Phase 4 — Offline-Online Validation: backtest on known good and bad launches, correlate judge metrics with business outcomes, and detect reward hacking against the judge",
    "Phase 5 — Production: monitor score drift, refresh gold sets, control evaluation cost, and preserve audit trails for launch approvals"
  ],
  "full_response": "I would begin by clarifying exactly what the platform is judging and how the scores will be used. The outputs could be recommendation lists, generated queries, summaries, or conversational responses, and each one has different quality dimensions. I would explicitly define a taxonomy such as relevance, diversity, novelty, safety, faithfulness, and business-rule compliance. The evaluation platform should not act as a single oracle. Its job is to provide a consistent offline signal for regression testing, model selection, and launch approval, alongside business guardrails and sampled human review.\n\nThe architecture starts with surface-specific rubrics rather than one universal judge prompt. For each product surface, I would create a structured rubric with dimension-level definitions and 1-5 scoring criteria. The judge input should include the anchor context, user intent if available, the model output being evaluated, and any supporting metadata. The judge should return structured JSON with per-dimension scores, an overall score, and short reasoning. For high-stakes launches, I would consider multiple judge prompts or even multiple models to reduce variance, while cheaper launches could use a single judge path. Cost matters, so I would evaluate launch candidates, sampled traffic, or regression suites, not every production request.\n\nCalibration is the most important part because a judge that sounds smart but does not match humans is dangerous. I would build human-labeled gold sets per surface and locale with clear annotation guidelines. Then I would measure agreement using metrics like weighted kappa, rank correlation, or pairwise preference agreement depending on the task. From there I would calibrate thresholds into decision buckets such as ship, investigate, and block. When the judge and humans disagree, that case should go into a disagreement queue so we can determine whether the rubric is underspecified, the prompt is biased, or the human guideline itself is inconsistent.\n\nTo prove the platform matters, I would connect offline judge scores to online outcomes. The strongest method is backtesting on prior launches where we already know the winner and loser. If the judge consistently ranks the winning launches higher, that builds trust. I would also correlate judge dimensions with business outcomes like CTR, attach rate, retention, complaint rate, or safety incident rate depending on the surface. But I would be explicit that correlation is not enough. A team can optimize against the judge directly and create reward hacking, where offline scores improve while user value does not. So I would keep a holdout human review process and treat judge scores as one launch gate input, not the only one.\n\nIn production, the evaluation platform itself needs monitoring. I would track score distribution drift after any base-model, prompt, or rubric update, refresh gold sets regularly, and rerun calibration when the product changes. For cost control, I would use tiered evaluation depth: lightweight heuristics or small judge prompts for routine checks, richer rubrics for risky launches. If judge quality degrades, the fallback is human review or a simpler heuristic gate. Finally, every launch decision should be auditable, with stored judge version, rubric version, prompt version, and evidence, so teams can understand why a launch passed or failed and we can debug bad decisions later."
}'::jsonb
WHERE category = 'design' AND subcategory = 'LLM Judge Evaluation Platform';
